      "text": "eisenstien triples are formed with side lengths of W,F,Z\n\nIntro\n0:00\nWelcome to another Mathologer  \n0:06\nvideo. You are all familiar with the diagram over there, right? Yes, of course, it’s the diagram powering the Mathologer logo :) Yeees, but that’s\n0:17\nnot really it, right? I am sure for the majority of people watching this video this diagram will scream \"Pythagoras\".\n0:23\nIf this is not the case, ask for your money back from your school and definitely keep\n0:28\non watching for a, hopefully, life changing experience. And even for those of you who’ve treasured this twisted square diagram since primary\n0:36\nschool keep watching. Today will be about all the secrets of this iconic diagram that not even most professional\n0:43\nmathematicians will be familiars with. But first a bit of revision to get us all on the same page.\n0:49\nA squared plus B squared equals C squared. You all know the drill. Take any right-angled triangle with short sides A and B and hypotenuse C. Then the\n1:00\narea of the square on the hypotenuse, C squared, is equal to the combined area of the squares\n1:05\non the two shorter sides, A squared plus B squared. A stunning visual proof of this fundamental mathematical truth runs like this.\n1:15\nTake four copies of the triangle and combine them into a large square like this.\n1:22\nOkay, this large square is partly covered by the four triangles. The area that is not covered is what?\n1:28\nWell, C squared of course. Now move one of the little triangles a bit.\n1:34\nHow large is the blue area now? Well, still C squared of course.\n1:39\nHow about now? Still C squared. And this will be true no matter how we position the triangles inside the blue square as long\n1:46\nas they don’t overlap. Right? Okay, ready for a big AHA moment :) Move the triangles one more time.\n1:53\nNo overlaps and so the area is still C squared. However, this area is also A squared plus B squared.\n2:01\nAnd so A squared plus B squared equals C squared. What an amazingly simple and beautiful proof and what a killer punchline, don’t you think!\n2:09\nAlright, now, how about this... The area of the large square is equal to the area of the little square plus the area of\n2:20\nthe four triangles Okay, the area of the large square is A plus B squared.\n2:26\nThe area of the little square is C squared. And the area of one of the right-angled triangles is 1/2 base times height, 1/2 A times B. Now\n2:37\nsimply go on algebra autopilot.\n2:49\nFantastic again. Maybe not quite as fantastic as the first proof but still fantastic. Just out of interest, can you let me know in the comments which of these two twisted\n2:59\nsquare proofs you were already familiar with and when and where you first came across them. Will be interesting.\n3:05\nOf course, most kids never get to see either proof, which in my book is a crime which should\n3:11\nentitle them to get their money back from their schools. As well, most school textbooks that feature a proof only mention the second less spectacular\n3:19\nalgebraic one. Go figure. Anyway, no matter how pretty these proofs are, that’s really all there is to this\n3:26\niconic diagram. Right? Wrong! There is more, lots and lots more.\n3:32\nThere is Fermat’s four square theorem, the TRIthagorean theorem, the bug chasing vortex,\n3:38\nand much more. Ready to be amazed. Here we go.\n3:43\nThe twisted square diagram has been around for a couple thousand years and features in the earliest documented proof of Pythagoras theorem which is part of an ancient Chinese\n3:52\nmanuscript on astronomy and mathematics. Well, Pythagoras neither discovered “his” theorem nor was he the first to prove it and\n4:00\nso to have this theorem named after him is really a bit of a scandal in mathematics. Anyway, let’s have a look inside the manuscript.\n4:07\nWhat you find there is pages upon pages of this.\n4:13\nLots and lots of Chinese characters. However, eventually we come across a page featuring our diagram.\n4:22\nWell, that’s definitely our diagram. But there is a bit more to this drawing, isn’t there?\n4:27\nThere, a second very different twisted square diagram made up of the same four right angled\n4:33\ntriangles. In fact, this second diagram can also be used to prove Pythagoras theorem in two different\n4:42\nways, one algebraic and one one based on shuffling triangles. Just looking at areas again we have: Four times the area of the triangle plus the area\n4:52\nof the little square is equal to the area of the large square. Expressing this identity in terms of A, B and C, and some algebra auto-pilot spits out\n5:01\nA squared plus B squared equals C squared in pretty much exactly the same way as before. On the other hand, the C squared area of the large square stays unchanged when we move\n5:12\nsome of the triangles. And so C squared is equal to A squared plus B squared.\n5:19\nAlso a very pretty proof and in a way even slicker than the first triangle shuffle proof\n5:24\nsince we only have to shuffle two of the triangles instead of all four.\n3 Squares: Fermat\u0027s four square theorem\n5:34\nThe Chinese drawing also features a grid. What’s that grid for? Well, it’s clear that no matter what right-angled triangle you start with, everything we said\n5:43\nso far will stay true. Of course, this is very important. Otherwise none of our proofs would actually count as a general proof of Pythagoras theorem.\n5:52\nOn the other hand, the grid shows that in our example, we are dealing with a super famous\n5:58\nright-angled triangle. Can you see it? Yep, it’s a 3-4-5 right-angled triangle. 3 squared plus 4 squared equals 5 squared.\n6:08\n3,4,5 the prototype Pythagorean triple, a triple of integers that satisfies the equation\n6:14\nA squared + B squared equals C squared. Since we’ve all been familiar with the 3,4,5 triple since kindergarten, we are taking the\n6:22\nfact that such special triples exist for granted. That the existence of such integer triples  is in fact a little bit of  a miracle is illustrated\n6:30\nby Fermat’s last theorem which says that if you change the exponent to 3 , 4 , or any\n6:37\nother larger integer the equation will not have any positive integer solutions.\n6:42\nBut of course, the wonderful 3,4,5 Pythagorean triple does exist.\n6:48\nAnd you can get more of these wonderful integer triples by simply changing the number of lines in the grid.\n6:53\nThere, doubling the number of gridlines give this 6 squared plus 8 squared equals 10 squared.\n7:01\nAnd tripling gives this But there are also other essentially different Pythagorean triples\n7:07\nand many of you will be familiar with this particular one. 5, 12, 13, 5 squared + 12 squared equals 13 squared.\n7:15\nAnyway, there are infinitely many essentially different Pythagorean triples and let me just\n7:21\nmention that we know how to construct all of them. And of course we can use any of these triples to make up one of these diagrams.\n7:29\nBut let’s stick with 3,4,5. Alright, let’s have another close look. How many squares are there?\n7:36\nWell there is this one Then that one And one more The area of the little square is ..... 1\n7:43\nsquared the area of this green square is 5 squared and what about the largest one?\n7:52\nWell 3+4 is 7 and so the area is 7 squared. Cool Now, what’s 25 - 1 25-1 that’s 24 of course.\n8:05\nWhat about 49 minus 25? You got it? 49 minus 25 is also 24 :) Interesting, both differences are the same.\n8:15\nIs that a coincidence? What do you think? Well, no, that we get the same difference is always true and really easy to see.\n8:23\nHave a look. What’s the difference between blue and green? Well that’s just the area of four copies of our right-angled triangle.\n8:32\nAnd how about the difference between the green and the orange. Same thing.\n8:39\nVery pretty isn’t it? So what this means is that within the square numbers we can find three equally spaced squares\n8:49\nand that every Pythagorean triple